tikv/tikv#18616.body:
Currently, TiKV supports bandwidth-based rate limiting for background auto-analyze requests (via [#12679](https://github.com/tikv/tikv/pull/12679)). However, background requests may trigger intensive IOPS bursts that exceed the IOPS quota on cloud environments, even when bandwidth usage is relatively low. This can degrade overall disk performance, impacting foreground latencies.

We are exploring whether it is feasible to introduce IOPS-based limiting for background requests — particularly for auto-analyze jobs. It remains to be investigated, but we might be able to leverage the RocksDB PerfContext counters to achieve this :
```
// rocksdb/include/rocksdb/perf_context.h
struct PerfContextBase {
    uint64_t block_read_count;  // total number of block reads (with IO)
}
```

tikv/tikv#18999.body:
## Bug Report
The reproduction unit test if the number of runtime worker threads are less than 11. The async task who hold the `DashMap` mutex is scheduled out because the async `Pending` while every worker thread running the async task trying to lock the `DashMap` mutex. Therefore the deadlock occurs.
```
components/sst_import/src/caching/cache_map.rs
mod tests {
    ...


    #[derive(Clone, Default)]
    struct AsyncCacheChecker(std::sync::Arc<AtomicBool>);
    impl MakeCache for AsyncCacheChecker {
        type Cached = ();
        type Error = Infallible;

        fn make_cache(&self) -> std::result::Result<Self::Cached, Self::Error> {
            self.0.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
            futures::executor::block_on(async {
                tokio::time::sleep(std::time::Duration::from_secs(10)).await;
            });
            Ok(())
        }
    }

    #[tokio::test]
    async fn test_deadlock() {
        let rt = tokio::runtime::Builder::new_multi_thread().worker_threads(4).enable_all().build().unwrap();
        let cached = CacheMap::default();

        let mut joins = Vec::new();
        for _ in 0..10 {
            let cached_cloned = cached.clone();
            let j = rt.spawn(async move {
                let c = AsyncCacheChecker::default();
                cached_cloned.cached_or_create("hello", &c).unwrap();
            });
            joins.push(j);
        }
        for j in joins {
            j.await.unwrap();
        }
    }
}
```

tikv/tikv#19299.body:
ref https://github.com/pingcap/tidb/issues/65659

 When a DAG TableScan request includes _tidb_commit_ts (EXTRA_COMMIT_TS_COL_ID = -5) in TableScan::columns, and the request also contains PK handle columns, TiKV assumes _tidb_commit_ts is located after all PK handle columns. If it’s placed before some PK handle columns, TableScanExecutorImpl::build_column_vec may allocate the commit-ts column as raw, but later process_kv_pair fills it via mut_decoded().push_int(...), leading to a panic / incorrect column type handling.

The below test case will panic:

```
#[test]
fn test_select_with_commit_ts_column_before_pk_handle() {
    use tidb_query_datatype::{FieldTypeAccessor, FieldTypeTp};

    let data = vec![
        (1, Some("name:0"), 2),
        (2, Some("name:4"), 3),
        (4, Some("name:3"), 1),
        (5, Some("name:1"), 4),
    ];

    let product = ProductTable::new();
    let (_, endpoint, _) = init_with_data_ext(&product, &data);

    let mut commit_ts_col = tipb::ColumnInfo::default();
    commit_ts_col.set_column_id(tidb_query_datatype::codec::table::EXTRA_COMMIT_TS_COL_ID);
    commit_ts_col.as_mut_accessor().set_tp(FieldTypeTp::LongLong);

    let mut select = DagSelect::from(&product);
    select
        .execs
        .get_mut(0)
        .unwrap()
        .mut_tbl_scan()
        .mut_columns()
        .insert(0, commit_ts_col);
    select.output_offsets = Some(vec![1, 2, 3]);

    let req = select.build();
    let mut resp = handle_select(&endpoint, req);
    let spliter = DagChunkSpliter::new(resp.take_chunks().into(), 3);
    for (row, (id, name, cnt)) in spliter.zip(data) {
        let name_datum = name.map(|s| s.as_bytes()).into();
        let expected_encoded = datum::encode_value(
            &mut EvalContext::default(),
            &[Datum::I64(id), name_datum, cnt.into()],
        )
        .unwrap();
        let result_encoded = datum::encode_value(&mut EvalContext::default(), &row).unwrap();
        assert_eq!(result_encoded, &*expected_encoded);
    }
}
```
